 St. Hesper's Asylum for the Criminally Mischievous, Nov. 12, 1929

You blink your eyes open. Where are you? The last thing you remember, you were minding your own business... well, actually you had just infiltrated the Moldenburg Street Fruit Market and snatched a bright shiny apple from some fat stupid fruitmonger's cart.  You started to leg it, when, from out of nowhere, dozens of constables descended on you, waving billy clubs like so! Crumbs! The whole thing was a set up from the start! A ruse! A cheat just so the fuzz could finally pinch Lil' Ragamuffin, the most daring, most dangerous street urchin to ever skitter the historic cobblestone streets of Garbagetown DC!

A very prim and proper cough interrupts your thoughts. You leap to your feet and assume a fighting stance, ready to rumble! You see an older woman, thick around the hips and middle, her brown-and-gray streaked hair pulled into a tight bun, cats-eye spectacles perched at the end of her pointed nose, thin lips pursed, wearing a tightly cinnched labcoat, her gloved hands clutching a clipboard.

"Calm down, please. We're not going to hurt you."

"'Course ya ain't! Ain't no one who can hurt Lil' Ragamuffin! I ain't a'scared of you! I is the roughest, toughest street urchin in Garbagetown DC an' nobody's sweetheart!"

"Oh my, the toughest?" She checks her clipboard. "I was informed you were only Garbagetown's SECOND most wanted urchin, though."

You bristle at the reminder. "I should be number one. I is the toughest an' you'd do well ta remember it!"

"I see.  That's why you're here.  We're going to cure you of that attitude. Welcome to St. Hesper's Asylum for the Criminally Mischievous. I'm Asylum Director Dr. Belladonna Caligazzi."

For the first time since you woke up, you take a look around the room. It's a small cramped room with black basalt walls, empty save for an old cot and a chamberpot.

"Holy schlamoley! I's in the hoosegow!?"

"Hmm, you might say that. We prefer to think of it as a sanitarium. The Urchinfinder General brought you here, so we could work on that. It took 15 officers and twenty truncheons to bring you down, so we all know you've got, er, fighting spirit. But we've been successful in treating even more rebellious urchins than you and turning them into good little girls and boys."

"Bah! I ain't never been good an' I never will be! Crumbs to that! No hoosegow ever gonna keep me! Jest you wait an' see, I'll escape quickern' you can say Jack Robinson!"

"Hmm, we'll be working on that attitude as well.  For now, though, I'd recommend you relax and make yourself at home."  She turns to leave.

"Hey! Ain'tcha gonna tie me up? I'm a dangerous urchin! A real tough cookie! Public enemy number one!"

"Number two. And no, that's not the way we do things at St. Hesper's. We're very modern; we believe in allowing patients free run of the premises."

"Ha! That's yer first mistake! I'll be outta here in two shakes of a lamb's tail!"

"No, you won't.  We allow you free roam of the facilities, but our security is top notch. No patient has ever escaped from St. Hesper's. the only way out is with discharge papers signed by yours truly. And I keep a constant eye on everything that happens in the asylum."

"St. Hesper's is equipped with the most modern in panopticon technology. You do know what a panopticon is, don't you?"

"Uhhh..."

"Well, the important thing is that, from my panopticon, I can see everything that happens in this entire asylum, so you won't be able to take a step without me knowing about it. That means escape is absolutely impossible. But, of course, I'd certainly be interested to see you try. It would provide me with some notes to discuss during your therapy. And who knows? If you escape, maybe the Urchin Finder General will even raise the bounty on you to make you the NUMBER ONE most wanted urchin."

"Yeah! That's right! Just you wait!"

You grumble to yourself as Dr. Caligazzi's footsteps recede into the distance.  "Lousy fancypants asylum director, who does she think she is? Tellin' Lil' Ragamuffin that she can't escape! I'll show her: I'll be outta here in no time an' the Urchin Finder General will TOTALLY have to declare me public enemy number ONE! Ha!"

You pause. "Oy! Percy? You here?"  Oh no! Percy! You forgot all about him!  Panicked, you quickly pat down your pockets, hoping that the constables haven't taken away your best pal!

"I'm right here, Rags!" says a large sewer rat, poking his pointed snout out from under your newsie cap.

"Oh criminy, don't scare me like that, Percy! I was afraid the bulls done took ya away! Did ya hear all that hogwash that hotsy totsy wuz spillin'? Sayin' we can't escape!"

"I did indeed, Rags," says Percy. Some folks might think it odd that a rat could talk. But Percy ain't no ordinary rat; he did go to Oxford, after all! "And I would suggest that we get out of here as soon as possible. I don't know what this treatment she talking about entails, but I don't want to hang around to find out."

"Sounds like the elephant's in-step ta me, Percy, I'm on board! Let's skadoodle!"

You are in a cell.
You can see a chamber pot, a cot and a clipboard.
You can go east.

This cell is NOT built for comfort. The bare stone walls are cold to the touch, and the only furnishings are a threadbare cot in the corner and a cracked chamberpot.  The only light comes from a widow set high into the black basalt wall.  The iron door opens to a hallway to the east.

