You are in an office.
You can see a psychiatrist and a chaise longue.
You can go west.
A comfortable, oak-lined office. The warm, cream-colored walls are covered in diplomas and certificates. A potted ficus stands in the corner, behind an overstuffed chaise longue. A young man sitting in a plush armchair turns to face you, a friendly smile on his face, as you enter.

You feel suddenly at ease when you enter, a unique sense of peace and welcome settling over you as you cross the threshold.

The young man looks up as you enter the room, a nervous puppy dog grin on his face.  "Oh hello, welcome to my office, I'm Alfie.. I... no, no, no, that's all wrong! I mean, I'm Dr. Deckchair, how can I help you? Oh gosh, darn it all, that didn't sound too unprofessional, did it? I'm so sorry, it's my first day on the job."
> x Alfie

> x Alfie
He's a baby-faced young man, probably in his mid-twenties, wearing a stylish tweed jacket with matching vest and bowtie. A bit of fuzz is visible on his upper lip, but he hasn't yet been able to successfully cultivate a mustache. He nervously clutches a pencil and steno pad in his hands.
> x longue

> x longue
It's a plush fainting couch upholstered in awful tacky faux leather.
> speak to Alfie

> speak to Alfie
"Hi there! Are you a patient? I mean, of course you are, why would you even be here if you weren't? Oh bother, I've botched the whole introduction... I'm so sorry, this is my first week on the job and I'm just so nervous. I did just make a fool of myself, didn't I?"

He looks to be near tears, so you can't help but feel bad for him.  "Naw, friend, it's all good. Yer doin' fine."

"Oh good! Gosh, thanks! I'm still getting the hang of it... but if you're here to get well... I mean, if you're... maybe I can help you?"

"I dunno, Doc, I ain't got any brain bugs," you say, tapping your forehead. "All my sweet meats is workin' like a tin lizzy right offa production!"

The doctor's face falls. "Oh, never mind then. I thought maybe... you had something I could help you with. I guess if you DO think of anything, just hop up on the chaise longue and we can get started diagnosing."
> ask him about himself

> ask him about himself
